comments.body:
Indeed, to match the previous version 100% the code would look something like this:
```C++
    ...
    // Convenience: OP_ADD and just ADD are both recognized:
    auto pos = strName.find("OP_");
    if (pos != std::string::npos) {
        strName = strName.substr(0, pos) + strName.substr(pos+3);
        mapOpNames[strName] = static_cast<opcodetype>(op);
    }
    ...
```
That would also eliminate an "OP_" substring that is _not_ at the start of `strName`. Don't know though if that really makes sense to match the previous version 100% (which did more than needed -- pos will always be either 0 or npos)? I guess it's a matter of taste and how strict a refactoring is defined.

